Prefectural Fishery Federation "Start discussion toward full-scale operation" Chairman Nozaki "Iwaki Minpo Official Website"
With the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant accident at TEPCO, discussions for full-scale operation of test operations off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture were made in each district.
Mr. Tetsu Nozaki, President of the Federation of Fisheries Cooperatives of the prefecture, said, "As the Federation of Fisheries Cooperatives of the prefecture, we believe that the flow toward full-scale operation is necessary, and we hope that the representatives will gather and start discussions."
The Union Presidents' Association also approved the official addition of casago, sakura trout, and murasoi off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture to the target species for test operations.
The remaining undisclosed marine products were two fish species, Vinosgai and Common Cusbe.
At the end of the meeting, President Nozaki told reporters that the start of full-scale operations has not yet been decided.
In response to the water treatment after purifying contaminated water at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, Mr. Yoshiaki Harada, former Minister of the Environment, and Ichiro Matsui, mayor of Osaka City, said, "There is a question of Keren-tasting debate, and the position against the release of the ocean remains unchanged."
In discussing the full-scale operation, Akira Egawa, head of Iwaki City Fisheries Cooperative, pointed out that "it is necessary to suck up opinions from the bottom," and said that it respects the intentions of the members.
It is said that a board meeting of subordinate branches is held to resolve the problems one by one, and the conclusion as a city fishing cooperative is reached.
Kanji Tachiya, head of the Soma Futaba Fishery Cooperative, said, "In addition to the fishermen, it is necessary to discuss it with the buyers."
The Soma Futaba Fisheries Cooperative is supported by the government and seven new ships will enter next year.
