"I hope South Korea will return to GSOMIA." - Yahoo!
U.S. Undersecretary of State for South Korea and Japan, Napper, in an interview with the Sankei Shimbun at the U.S. Ambassador's residence in Tokyo, said on November 27 that he hoped that Korea would reconsider and return to its decision to destroy Japan and Korea's comprehensive military information protection agreement (GSOMIA), which expires on November 23.
It is unusual for a senior U.S. official to mention a reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, South Korea, the United States, the United States, and South Korea to share missile launch information.
South Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan in August, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse in Japan and South Korea.
Napper argued that "without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to crises."
He strongly urged the return of Korea, saying, "There is time until revocation."
He also pointed out that the joint flight training conducted by China and Russia in July over the Sea of Japan was "the first time in history" and said, "It is essential that the United States, Korea and Japan, which share values such as democracy and human rights, collaborate in alliance relations."
He pointed out that the recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations "damaged the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of intermediation," he said, "Japan and Korea will play a positive role to fill the gap."
(Yusuke HIRATA)
Tokai-mura criticality accident, 20 years in 30 days 300 nuclear facility troubles: Hokkaido Shimbun
The Nuclear Regulation Authority (NRA) reported 336 accidents and failures that occurred at nuclear facilities across Japan between 2000 and 2006 following the critical accident in Tokai-mura, Ibaraki Prefecture, the first in the history of nuclear power in Japan.
It has been 30 days and 20 years since the critical accident that alarmed the safety myth of the nuclear industry.
According to the report, although the International Assessment Scale (INES), which shows seriousness, accounted for about 90% of items that were not evaluated or evaluated, it is necessary to raise safety awareness without fail based on lessons learned from the accident and the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant accident of Tokyo Electric Power Co., Ltd. in 2011.
Koichi Soda, who has completed the story and original drawings of creative picture books, is seeking donations for publication.
Koichi Soda (64), an artist from the Echizen City Regional Development Cooperation Volunteer in Fukui Prefecture, started a crowdfunding campaign aimed at publishing creative picture books inspired by legends in Fukui Prefecture in order to promote town development using picture books.
Mr. Soda, who came from Hokkaido and started his activities as a member of the cooperative group in April this year, says, "I want to convey the hearts of the people of Fukui based on deep faith through picture books."
[Donation is here] To convey the heart of Fukui.
Mr. Soda has been active as an artist working on contemporary art based on mathematics, while he has also been active as a member of the cooperative team since past the calendar.
After working on the town development of Nagano, Kumamoto and Tochigi, he joined Echizen City in April this year.
The city, which produced Riko Kako and Chihiro Iwasaki, aims to create a town that makes use of picture books.
Mr. Soda lived in the city and said, "I was surprised by the depth of compassion around me for the first time."
What attracted attention was the legend of the city of Awara, "The face of the demon of the bride Odoshi."
It is a story that a heart-friendly bride continues to chant Nenbutsu (Buddhist invocation) to help her mother without worrying about being surprised by her face.
"I forgot my hatred and returned with kindness and kindness, and I felt the origin of the faith and kindness of the people of Fukui."
Inspired by the original picture book, Soda went to Yoshizaki Gobo in Awara City as soon as he arrived, and made the story "Meoto Oni" with a loving couple and a boy.
From June, he drew 10 scenes with warm watercolors, taking advantage of his job, and the materials of picture books were scattered.
In addition, the cover of the picture book will be made with washi using Echizen washi, a traditional craft that lives in Echizen City.
This leads to an opportunity for parents and children to enjoy the touch of Japanese paper through reading and listening.
The goal of the donation amount is 850,000 yen for 600 copies.
The deadline is October 25.
Mr. Soda said, "Fukui's heart, which has been nurtured under the historical Buddhist culture, is proud throughout Japan.
I want to tell children what true kindness and compassion are handed down through picture books."
Fukui Prefecture is one of the projects in which Fukui Prefecture certifies 11 projects for regional revitalization that are challenged by local cooperatives and businesses in the prefecture, and supports them by utilizing hometown tax.
The Fukui Shimbun publishes information and the Fukui Bank cooperates with management support.
Donations can be made from the crowdfunding website Lady For.
