Okayama Art Exchange Opens in the City Center: Sanyo Shimbun Digital | San'Digi
People who go around the classroom in a video work depicting the future 3,000 years later = Former Uchiyamashita Elementary School
The international art exhibition "Okayama Art Exchange 2019" held every three years in central Okayama City (hosted by the executive committee of cities, prefectures, etc.) opened on the 27th.
Along with the mysterious title "IF THE SNAKE If Snake," 18 artists from 9 countries enjoy cutting-edge art.
This time, the second time since 16 years, we have invited French artist Pierre Yuig as artistic director to develop works that utilize Okayama's climate and local resources.
Approximately 40 films and three-dimensional works will be shown at 13 locations including the former Uchiyamashita Ko (Marunouchi, Kita Ward, Okayama City) and the prefectural Tenjinyama Cultural Plaza (Tenjin-cho, Okayama City).
Prior to the opening ceremony, a small opening ceremony was held, and about 100 people attended.
Mayor Masao Omori and General Producer Yasuharu Ishikawa, the chairman of the executive committee, said, "The works that stimulate intellectual sensibilities and stimulate imagination and creativity have come together, and it will become an exhibition that attracts attention from the world."
Families and children studying outside the school visited the school immediately and found a snake-shaped robot that responds to the surrounding sounds in the dohyo of the school yard, and walked around the school building, which turned into a stage for video works depicting the world 3,000 years later.
I enjoyed the art that led to different worlds.
While traveling with my father, a first-year high school student in Tokyo (15) said, "It's interesting to make use of the atmosphere of the old school building, and I can imagine the time that flows into this place."
It is closed on Mondays (in case of public holidays) until November 24.
Meeting in Hong Kong, 5 years of the Umbrella Movement tens of thousands, aiming for a general election | Shizuoka Shimbun at Es
Five years have passed since the "Umbrella Movement" started, and people gathered at the meeting hall = 28th, Hong Kong (joint)
[Collaboration with Hong Kong] On the 28th of May 2014, a large-scale demonstration called the "Umbrella Movement" was held in the park near the Hong Kong Government Office Building in Admiralty, where the largest demonstration unit was located.
Some young people occupied the main road around the venue and threw fire bottles into the government building.
As protests began with the amendment of the Fugitive Ordinance continued, the participants renewed their determination to fight until the realization of a "true ordinary election" that could not be won at the time.
In June, more than 79 days after the Umbrella Movement, 112 days of protests began, and the demands of the demonstrators expanded to "five major demands" such as electoral reform.
Ibaraki Kokutai Opening Day|Saga Newspaper News|Saga Newspaper
The 74th National Sports Festival "Ikiiki Ibaraki Yume Kokutai 2019" will be held on October 28 at Kasamatsu Sports Park Athletic Stadium in Hitachinaka City, Ibaraki Prefecture.
About 400 players and coaches from Saga Prefecture will participate in 33 competitions, excluding those held before the exhibition.
The prefecture ranked 43rd for three consecutive years until last year, but rose to 33rd last year.
We are strengthening our efforts toward the national sports tournament held in the prefecture in 2023, and this year we aim to reach the first half of the 20th place.
In the pre-event before the 16th session, the Saga Girls' High School of rhythmic gymnastics and the adult girls and boys' girls of gymnastics all won sixth place and played.
I would like to aim to advance to the top in each competition.
At the general opening ceremony, 83 athletes, directors, and officers of the headquarters of the prefecture marched on the 40th entrance, and a rugby boy, Kugo Ishikawa (Saga Koka), was the flag bearer.
On the first day, wrestling, table tennis and karate are held.
